# Cyrius Field Notes — Compiler Internal Gotchas
# Non-obvious traps an agent will hit when working on cyrius's
# compiler internals: regalloc, layout, alignment, IR ordering,
# heap caps, fn-table conventions, codegen-vs-IR divergence.
#
# Earn their slot when an agent is debugging a cyrius
# regression that doesn't fit a clean pattern. The shape is
# always "this surprised future-me; here's the diagnosis +
# fix + how to recognize it again."
#
# For process methodology see methodology.cyml.
# For design patterns see patterns.cyml.
# For full backstory + chronological context see retros/.
#
# 20 entries.

[[entries]]
name = "slice_fn_local_layout_flip"
description = "Pre-§8 16-byte fn-local slices put the canonical slot at the higher stack address; `&slice + 8` overflowed past the local frame into saved-rbp territory. §8 layout-flip (v5.8.16) allocates the high-half slot FIRST (higher address) and the canonical slot SECOND (lower address)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["slices", "layout", "stack", "v5.8.16"]
content = """
**The trap**: pre-v5.8.16, `var s: [u8] = 0;` allocated a
single canonical slot (the named slot, where `&s` resolves)
and a sentinel-cleared high-half slot. The canonical slot was
the LOWER-numbered slot (higher stack address per cyrius's
slot-N-at-rbp-(N+1)*8 convention). `slice_set(&s, ptr, len)`
did `store64(s+8, len)`, which on the stack means
`store64(rbp - canon_disp + 8, len)` — overflowing past the
local frame into saved-rbp territory.

This corrupted the caller's saved rbp. Worked anyway:

  1. Round-tripped within the fn — slice_set wrote and slice_len
     read the same (corrupted) location.
  2. `slices_typing.tcyr`'s `return slice_len(&x);` form passed
     because main's rbp = 0 from the C runtime — the read
     returned 0 by coincidence.
  3. §7 indexing tests passed because each test exited via
     `syscall(60, ...)` before any code referenced the corrupted
     rbp.

**Surfaced when**: §8 introduced `s.len` reads via &s+8
(memory I/O through the canonical-slot address) — same
arithmetic as slice_set, but the test reading expected a
deterministic value, not "whatever happened to be at saved rbp."

**Fix**: for `scalar_type==16`, allocate the HIGH-HALF slot
FIRST (slot li, higher address) and the CANONICAL slot SECOND
(slot li+1, lower address). The name + meta live on slot li+1
so FINDLOCAL returns it; EFLADDR(li+1) yields the lower
address; EFLADDR(li+1) + 8 lands on slot li (higher address) —
matching the slice convention's "second 8 bytes."

Init both halves: zero the canonical slot via EFLSTORE(li+1)
and zero the high half via address-based memory store
(EFLADDR_X1 + EADDIMM_X1(8) + ESTOC). Address-based init for
the high half is required because the regalloc post-body
peephole would patch EFLSTORE(li) to `mov rbx, rax` (writing
to a register, not the stack slot). See `slice_high_half_regalloc_pin`.

**Recognize again**: any "fn-local 16-byte type silently fails"
shape. If two adjacent `var x: u128` or `var s: [T]` interact
weirdly, check the layout-flip is still in place.

Full backstory: v5_8.cyml's `slice_fn_local_layout_flip_v5816`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "slice_high_half_regalloc_pin"
description = "Slice's high-half slot has no user-visible name; the regalloc post-body peephole would allocate a callee-saved register for it, leaving the actual stack slot uninitialized. §8 routes high-half I/O through address-based memory access to keep the slot in memory."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["slices", "regalloc", "v5.8.16"]
content = """
**The trap**: the regalloc post-body peephole (parse_fn.cyr
v5.6.20 picker) counts `mov [rbp+disp], rax` /
`mov rax, [rbp+disp]` patterns per slot to decide which user-
locals to pin to callee-saved registers (rbx, r12-r15). Time-
sliced sharing assumes every local interval starts with a STORE —
the register holds the right value from the start of each
interval, no LOAD-from-stack needed.

The slice's high-half slot has no user-visible name (sentinel-
cleared by the §8 layout-flip), so nothing else takes its
address via `&<ident>`. The picker's safety scan bars
`lea rax, [rbp+disp]` (treats `&local` as not-safe). Without
intervention, the high-half slot looks mov-only — picker
allocates rbx for it.

Then `var s: [T] = 0;`'s init `EFLSTORE(li, rax=0)` patches to
`mov rbx, rax` — writes 0 to rbx, leaves the stack slot
uninitialized. Subsequent slice_set memory-writes to the slot
are invisible to the register; `s.len` reads (which go through
the memory access path) see uninit stack data.

**Fix**: init the high half via address-based memory store
(EFLADDR_X1 + EADDIMM_X1(8) + ESTOC) rather than EFLSTORE.
The picker doesn't count memory-via-rcx writes, so the high
slot stays in memory. §8 dot-syntax (.len read/write) and
slice_len helper-fn calls all see the right value.

Same reasoning for §8 dot-syntax `s.len`: lower to address-
based load (EFLADDR_X1 + EADDIMM_X1(8) + ELODC), not direct
EFLLOAD against the slot. `s.ptr` could safely use EFLLOAD
(canonical slot is naturally barred from regalloc by slice_set
taking `&s`), but uses address-based for symmetry.

**Recognize again**: any "no-name auxiliary slot interacts
weirdly with regalloc" shape. The picker's safety scan only
bars slots with `&` taken via a NAMED ident; phantom slots
(high half of a 16-byte type, scratch slots) need explicit
exclusion.

Full backstory: v5_8.cyml's `slice_high_half_regalloc_pin_v5816`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "tail_call_escape_addr_local"
description = "PARSE_RETURN's tail-call detector now skips TCO if any arg in `return helper(args);` uses the `&` token. The TCO epilogue deallocates the current frame BEFORE the callee reads through `&local`."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["tco", "tail-call", "stack", "v5.8.16"]
content = """
**The trap**: pre-§8 TCO matched `return IDENT(args);` and
emitted normal call-arg setup, then the fn epilogue (restoring
callee-saved regs, popping rbp, restoring rsp), then
`jmp <callee>`. Inside the callee, the previous frame is gone —
anything the callee reads through a pointer to that frame sees
dead stack.

For most call patterns this never mattered — fn args are
passed by value (in registers). The exception: `&local` args.
`return helper(&local);` would compile to:

```
push &local (== rbp - local_disp)
pop rdi
...epilogue...
jmp helper
```

Inside helper, rdi = old caller's rbp - local_disp, but old
caller's frame is gone; reads through that address see
arbitrary stack memory.

**Pre-§8 was masked** for slice fn-locals because the slice's
high half coincidentally landed on saved rbp (= 0 from the
C runtime when called from main). The §8 layout-flip moved
the high half into a real stack slot, exposing the dead-
stack-read deterministically.

**Fix**: PARSE_RETURN scans the tail-call arg list for `&`
(token type 27); if present, skip TCO and emit a normal call.
Conservative — also blocks TCO for `&global` (rare and only
loses the optimization, not correctness).

**Why "skip" rather than "patch"**: the right fix would be
escape analysis on `&local` to bar TCO only when the local's
address actually escapes the call's lifetime. Cyrius doesn't
have escape analysis; the conservative skip is the right
trade-off given the rarity of `return helper(&local);`
patterns and the catastrophic cost of false-positives
(silently corrupted reads).

**Recognize again**: any "callee silently reads garbage when
called as `return helper(&local);`" shape.

Full backstory: v5_8.cyml's `tail_call_escape_addr_local_v5816`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "pointer_vs_inline_struct_dispatch"
description = "PARSE_FIELD_LOAD/STORE auto-detects pointer-to-struct vs inline-struct fn-locals by checking if slot lli-1 has the v5.5.36 sentinel name -1. Inline mode uses lea (slot IS the struct's bytes); pointer mode uses mov (slot HOLDS a pointer)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["struct", "field-access", "v5.8.17"]
content = """
**The trap**: PARSE_FIELD_LOAD's local-struct branch
historically treated EVERY struct-typed local as an INLINE
struct (the v5.5.36 no-init `var p: StructName;` path that
allocates ceil(STRUCTSZ/8) slots, named slot at the deepest
stack position). For inline structs, `&s` (EFLADDR(named_slot))
yields field 0's address because the struct's bytes ARE the
slot's bytes — `lea + offset + load` is correct.

But `var s: Str = str_from(...)` allocates ONE slot whose
value IS the heap pointer. `&s` in this case is the slot's
address (rbp - N), NOT the struct's address. `lea + offset +
load` reads the wrong location.

**Fix**: distinguish at PARSE_FIELD_LOAD time by checking slot
lli-1. The v5.5.36 inline path tags filler slots with sentinel
name -1; if slot lli-1 carries that sentinel (or lli == 0,
since inline structs always reserve a filler before the named
slot when STRUCTSZ > 8), the slot is the named tail of an
inline allocation. Otherwise it's a single-slot pointer.

Pointer mode emits `EFLLOAD + EMOVCA` (load slot value into
rax, move into rcx) to set rcx to the struct's base. Inline
mode emits `EFLADDR_X1` (lea — slot address IS the struct
base) as before.

Param-decl path also extended: PARSE_FN_DEF's param loop now
calls FINDSTRUCT on every `: Type` annotation; if the type
resolves to a struct, sets `SLTYPE(li, -sid)` on the param's
slot. Without this tag, `param.field` on a `: Str` parameter
would compile-error with "unexpected ',' / ';'" because the
struct-typed-local branch would never fire.

Disambiguation works for STRUCTSZ > 8 (Str at 16, Vec at 24,
etc.). For STRUCTSZ <= 8 (single-slot inline), the heuristic
falls through to inline mode (no sentinel above) — these
should be rare and the disambiguation can be revisited if a
consumer surfaces pain.

**Recognize again**: any "pointer-typed struct local + field
access reads zero" shape — verify the dispatch is firing.

Full backstory: v5_8.cyml's `pointer_vs_inline_struct_dispatch_v5817`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "stale_fixed_cap_drift"
description = "Cap checks drift out of sync with the actual buffer size. The buffer gets expanded; the cap check / comment / docs DON'T. Bug sits latent until a downstream workload crosses the OLD threshold."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["caps", "drift", "diagnostics", "v3.4.20", "recurring"]
content = """
**The trap pattern**: cyrius uses fixed-size heap regions for
nearly every compiler data structure. Each region has an
explicit byte count (e.g., tok_names is 64 KB, preprocess_out
is 2 MB at v5.6.40). Most regions have a "capacity check"
somewhere in the code that silently caps or errors out when
the region fills.

Multiple times now, a capacity check has drifted out of sync
with the actual buffer size. The pattern:

1. Buffer gets expanded in one place (the actual allocation).
2. Cap check / comment / docs DON'T get updated in the other
   places.
3. Bug sits latent for N releases.
4. Some downstream workload crosses the OLD threshold.
5. Confusing error fires that doesn't point at the real
   buffer.
6. Delayed debugging session to figure out the stale cap is
   lying.

**Concrete instances**:

- v3.3.17 (Bug #33): LEXHEX read hex literals from the raw
  input buffer instead of the preprocessed buffer. Masked for
  years.
- v3.4.19: input_buf read loop capped at 131,072 bytes (the
  original 128 KB) silently — mabda's 141 KB bundle triggered
  the latent bug.
- v3.4.20 (lex.cyr:1077): preprocess_out cap checked
  `op > 524288` (512 KB), but the buffer was expanded to 1 MB
  in v3.4.5. Stale for FIVE releases.
- v3.4.20 (cyrius.toml roadmap): documented Input buffer as
  512 KB while actual code was 128 KB then 256 KB. Three
  different numbers across three files.

**The proactive sweep** (do at every minor closeout):

For each fixed-size buffer in cyrius, grep for EVERY
occurrence of the capacity constant (allocation AND cap
check) and confirm they agree. Also check comments, heap map,
docs, roadmap, and Open Limits table — all four need to match.

The Open Limits table in `docs/development/roadmap.md` is
worth special attention — it's the table downstream projects
read to decide how much headroom they have.

**The diagnostic discipline** (every fixed-size buffer):

Every fixed-size buffer should have an EXPLICIT overflow check
with a CLEAR error message pointing at the exact location to
fix:

```cyr
if (op > 1048576) {
    syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2,
        "error: expanded source exceeds 1MB (", 36);
    PRNUM(op);
    syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2,
        " bytes; raise preprocess_out cap in src/main.cyr)\\n", 50);
    syscall(SYS_EXIT, 1);
}
```

Silent truncation is never acceptable — it moves the symptom
arbitrarily far from the cause.

**Recognize again**: any error message reporting a numeric
threshold that doesn't match the comment / heap map / Open
Limits table.

Cross-ref: patterns.cyml's
`heap_cap_growth_compiler_grows_to_fit_language` (the dual —
when to RAISE caps vs when to discover stale caps).

Full backstory: retros/v3.cyml `stale_fixed_cap_pattern` +
`silent_stdin_truncation_saga`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "stdlib_alloc_grow_step_must_cover_request"
description = "Bump-allocator grow logic must cover the requested allocation, not a fixed delta. Fixed step `0x100000` regardless of requested size returned pointers past the brk/mmap for any alloc(>1MB)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["alloc", "stdlib", "v5.6.x"]
content = """
**The trap**: bump allocator (`lib/alloc.cyr`) must grow its
backing region by AT LEAST the requested size, not a fixed
delta. Pre-fix, the grow logic was:

```cyr
if (alloc_used + n > brk_top) {
    sys_brk(brk_top + 0x100000);   # grow by 1 MB
    brk_top = brk_top + 0x100000;
}
return alloc_used; alloc_used = alloc_used + n;
```

For `alloc(1500000)` (1.5 MB request), the grow step adds 1 MB
but the requested size is 1.5 MB → returned pointer is past
the new brk_top. Subsequent stores write into unmapped memory
→ SIGSEGV.

**Fix**: grow by max(requested, fixed_step):

```cyr
if (alloc_used + n > brk_top) {
    var grow = 0x100000;
    if (n > grow) { grow = n + 0x100000; }
    sys_brk(brk_top + grow);
    brk_top = brk_top + grow;
}
```

**Recognize again**: any "alloc(N) for large N silently
SIGSEGVs in subsequent store" shape. Single-store SIGSEGVs
right after an alloc are almost always bump-allocator
boundary issues; print `alloc_used` and `brk_top` at the
crash site to confirm.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's
`stdlib_alloc_grow_step_vs_requested_size`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "libssl_needs_fdlopen_not_dynlib_open"
description = "libssl's OPENSSL_init_ssl uses a recursive pthread mutex whose __kind field lives in the glibc TCB. cyrius's dynlib_bootstrap_tls zeroed TCB reads __kind=0 (non-recursive); same-thread re-entry deadlocks on futex. Use lib/fdlopen.cyr (foreign-dlopen) instead."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["dynlib", "tls-loader", "fdlopen", "v5.6.37"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius has two ways to load shared libraries at
runtime:

1. `lib/dynlib.cyr` — pure-cyrius ELF .so loader via mmap +
   GNU hash table walk. No libc, no glibc dlopen. Bypasses
   glibc's TLS/TCB setup entirely.

2. `lib/fdlopen.cyr` — foreign-dlopen wrapper. Calls into
   glibc's actual dlopen via the AT_BASE+offset trick, which
   means the loaded library gets glibc's full TLS/TCB setup
   including pthread_*.

For libssl specifically, dynlib_open works for getting symbol
addresses — but calling `OPENSSL_init_ssl()` deadlocks on a
futex inside libcrypto's pthread_mutex_lock. Why: libssl's
init uses `PTHREAD_RECURSIVE_MUTEX_INITIALIZER_NP`. The mutex
struct has a `__kind` field in glibc's TCB. cyrius's
dynlib_bootstrap_tls (the minimal TLS setup that dynlib_open
provides) zeros the TCB. `__kind == 0` means "non-recursive"
in pthread's encoding. Same-thread re-entry to a mutex that
the same thread already holds → futex wait forever (because
non-recursive).

**Rule**: if a library's init function uses pthread mutexes
internally, you NEED fdlopen (real glibc dlopen → real glibc
TLS/TCB), not dynlib (cyrius minimal loader). The list of
libraries that hit this includes:

- libssl (OPENSSL_init_ssl)
- libpthread (everything)
- libgomp (OpenMP runtime)
- libc-internal locking primitives (rare in pure cyrius use,
  but anything that touches TLS-cancellation hooks)

Conversely, dynlib is fine for:

- Pure C libraries with no pthread internals (libz, libcrypto's
  primitive routines if you skip OPENSSL_init_*)
- Libraries you call only for symbol addresses (dlsym then
  call manually)

**Recognize again**: any "dlopen succeeds, dlsym returns valid
pointer, calling that pointer hangs forever" shape on a
shared library that uses pthread mutexes.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's `libssl_needs_fdlopen_not_dynlib_open`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "sysv_odd_stack_args_rsp_alignment"
description = "SysV ABI requires rsp 16-aligned at every CALL (so callee sees rsp+8 16-aligned at entry). Cyrius's ECALLPOPS for n>6 args used `add rsp, 48` unconditionally; for odd nextra (N=7,9,11) this left rsp 8-aligned at CALL, propagating misalignment."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["abi", "sysv", "alignment", "v5.6.41"]
content = """
**The trap**: SysV AMD64 ABI requires rsp 16-byte aligned at
every CALL instruction (so the callee sees rsp+8 16-byte
aligned at entry, with the saved rip below it). Cyrius's
codegen for fn calls with >6 args uses ECALLPOPS to clean up
stack arguments after the call:

```cyr
# n > 6 args, n_extra = n - 6
# Push n_extra extra args
# call helper
# add rsp, n_extra * 8  ← cleanup
```

Pre-v5.6.41, the cleanup was `add rsp, n_extra * 8`
unconditionally. For odd `n_extra` (N = 7, 9, 11 args), this
leaves rsp 8-byte-aligned at the next CALL. Misalignment
propagates downstream until something does SSE on a stack-
saved value (libssl/libc prologs commonly do `movdqa xmm,
[rsp+N]`) — SIGSEGV at first instruction.

**Fix**: align rsp to 16 BEFORE pushing extra args:

```cyr
if ((n_extra & 1) == 1) {
    # Pre-pad rsp by 8 to absorb odd n_extra count
    push rax  # any value; we sub rsp, 8 effectively
}
push n_extra args
call helper
add rsp, (n_extra + (n_extra_odd ? 1 : 0)) * 8
```

Win64 path was already correct via framesize-mod-15 alignment
branch; SysV path missed it.

**Recognize again**: any "SIGSEGV on the first SSE instruction
of a libc / libssl entry" shape. Common triggers: 7-arg fn
calls, OpenSSL's EVP_DecryptInit_ex (8 args), recvmmsg
(7 args). Always check rsp alignment via `gdb p $rsp & 0xF`
at the failing instruction.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's `sysv_odd_stack_args_rsp_alignment_violation`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "pp_pass_helpers_take_src_base"
description = "Preprocessor pass helpers (PP_HASH/DEFINE/DEFINED/GETVAL/EVAL_IF/DERIVE_*) must take src_base. Reading via S+pos for source > 524288 B lands in stale heap when PP_*_PASS copied content back to S+0 capped at 524288."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["preprocessor", "caps", "v5.6.30", "v5.6.42"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius's preprocessor runs in passes
(`PP_REF_PASS`, `PP_DERIVE_PASS`, `PP_IFDEF_PASS`, etc.). Each
pass reads source from one buffer, writes processed output to
another, then COPIES the output back to `S+0` for the next
pass to consume.

The copy-back is capped at 524288 B (the original
preprocess_out size). For source > 524 KB, the copy truncates;
helpers reading from `S+pos` for pos beyond 524 KB land in
stale heap (whatever was there before the pass).

v5.6.30 fixed this for `PP_DERIVE_*` helpers by threading
`src_base` through their signatures (so they read from the
actual buffer, not assumed-to-be-at-S+0).

v5.6.42 closed the rest of the family: `PP_HASH`, `PP_DEFINE`,
`PP_DEFINED`, `PP_GETVAL`, `PP_EVAL_IF`. Same shape — each
function gained a `src_base` arg that callers pass through
from the actual pass buffer.

**Recognize again**: any "preprocessor truncates / corrupts at
exactly 524 KB" shape. The fix is always "thread src_base
through the helper family"; never "raise the cap and hope."
Threading the argument is the structurally correct fix.

**Generalize**: any helper that reads from a region the caller
chose should TAKE THE REGION as an argument, not assume a
fixed offset. Hardcoded `S+pos` reads in helpers are a
recurring trap class.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's `pp_ifdef_pass_helpers_must_take_src_base`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "ts_lex_jsx_lookahead_terminators"
description = "TS_LOOKAHEAD_IS_ARROW's COLON-branch must treat JSX closing tokens as scope terminators or it false-positives on unrelated arrows far past the expression."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["ts", "lex", "jsx", "v5.7.6"]
content = """
**The trap**: when TS_LOOKAHEAD_IS_ARROW determines whether
`(` starts an arrow function, it scans for the matching `)`,
then checks what follows. If COLON, it enters a secondary
scan for `=>` (return-type form `(args): T => body`).

The COLON-branch's secondary scan tracked LPAREN/RPAREN/
LBRACKET/RBRACKET/LT/GT for depth, and treated LBRACE/SEMI/
COMMA at depth==0 as terminators. JSX tokens were SKIPPED —
none of them affected depth, none terminated.

For ternary `a ? (<JSX/>) : (<JSX2/>)` followed by REAL JSX
text + much later an arrow function in the same source: the
COLON-branch scanned past the else-branch's RPAREN
(depth → 0), past JSX closing tokens (JSX_EXPR_CLOSE,
JSX_CLOSE_END, etc. — all skipped), into adjacent code, and
FOUND an unrelated `=>` at depth==0. LOOKAHEAD returned 1
(arrow), parser entered ARROW_PAREN, then ARROW_PARAMS errored
on the JSX_OPEN_START at the start of `(<JSX/>)`.

**Fix**: COLON-branch treats `JSX_EXPR_CLOSE` /
`JSX_CLOSE_END` / `JSX_FRAGMENT_CLOSE` / `JSX_SELF_CLOSE` /
`JSX_OPEN_END` as terminators at depth==0. A closed-out JSX
construct can't be inside an arrow return-type position, so
`=>` past it is unrelated.

**Why this resisted bisect**: the bug requires (1) a ternary
with JSX-containing parens, (2) an unrelated arrow function
SOMEWHERE later in the same source. Single-line removal can't
isolate because it depends on TWO non-adjacent constructs.
Removing either suppresses it, neither was the culprit alone.

**Recognize again**: any "TS arrow-fn detection misfires on
file with mixed JSX + later arrow" shape. The fix is always
"the lookahead scan needs to terminate at the JSX construct's
close." Other lookaheads in the TS frontend may have similar
gaps (template literals, generic-arg lists, asserts predicate
clauses).

Full backstory: v5_7.cyml's `ts_lex_jsx_lookahead_is_arrow_jsx_terminators`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "fn_keyword_in_param_position"
description = "`fn` is a reserved keyword and cannot be used as a parameter name even in helper fns. Cyrius surfaces this with 'expected identifier, got reserved keyword fn' at the NEXT fn definition, not the offending one."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["parser", "diagnostics", "v5.7.46"]
content = """
**The trap**: writing `fn helper(fn, arg)` declares a
parameter named `fn`. Cyrius's parser treats `fn` as a
reserved keyword (token type 32), so this fails — but the
error message points at the WRONG location.

The parser first sees `fn helper(`, accepts it, then sees the
parameter list. When it tries to read `fn` as a parameter
name, it errors with "expected identifier, got reserved
keyword fn" — but the PARSE_TOKEN cursor is at the NEXT
function definition's `fn` keyword, not the one in the param
list. So the error reports the line of the next fn, not the
broken param.

Diagnosis is "the fn at line X is broken" → user inspects
line X → finds nothing wrong → confused.

**Fix at v5.7.46** (cyrius v5.5.26+ ERR_EXPECT enhancement):
when the expected token is type 2 (identifier) and the got
token is a keyword (IS_KEYWORD_TOK returns 1), the diagnostic
explicitly names the keyword:

```
error: expected identifier, got reserved keyword 'fn'
       (cannot be used as an identifier; rename the variable/
       field/fn)
```

The error fires at the keyword's actual line, not the next
fn. The "rename" hint helps users figure out the fix without
having to know which keywords are reserved.

**The reserved-keyword list** that triggers this: `fn`, `if`,
`else`, `elif`, `while`, `for`, `return`, `var`, `struct`,
`enum`, `union`, `match`, `defer`, `include`, `asm`, `kernel`,
`object`, `secret`, `in`, `shared`, `default`, `as`,
`continue`, `break`. Any of these as a param/local/struct-
field name surfaces the same error.

**Recognize again**: any "compile error 'expected
identifier' on a line that looks fine" shape. Check the
PREVIOUS fn's param list for keyword reuse.

Full backstory: v5_7.cyml's `fn_keyword_in_param_position`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "lsp_globals_before_fn_definitions"
description = "Cyrius requires top-level `var X` to be declared before any fn body that references X. Applies to programs/cyrius-lsp.cyr's symbol-table backing buffers too."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "lsp", "global-init-order", "v5.7.39"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius's parser does a single-pass top-down
walk of source. When a fn body references a top-level
`var X`, that `var X` must already be declared at parse time.
Forward fn calls work (the parser pre-scans fn signatures);
forward GLOBAL VAR references DO NOT work.

This is the v5.7.32 cyrlint warning class
(`global-init-order forward-ref`) that mabda surfaced. The
compiler ALSO doesn't catch every shape — the warning is
opt-in via `cyrius lint`.

**The cyrius-lsp specific instance** (v5.7.39): the LSP
extension added cross-file go-to-def + documentSymbol via a
symbol-table backing buffer. The buffer was a top-level `var
symbol_table[N]`. The fns that read it (`SYMBOL_LOOKUP`,
`SYMBOL_INSERT`) were defined before the `var` line in the
source layout.

Pre-fix: the parser saw the fn defs first, registered them,
parsed their bodies → reached `symbol_table` reference →
"undefined variable." Post-fix: moved `var symbol_table[N]`
above all fn defs that reference it.

**Recognize again**: any "undefined variable" error on a top-
level var that VISUALLY appears in the source somewhere.
Check it appears BEFORE the fns that read it.

**Generalize**: any new top-level `var X` declared in
cyrius's own source (or any cyrius project) MUST go above the
fn bodies that reference it. The parser is single-pass for
globals.

Full backstory: v5_7.cyml's `lsp_globals_before_fn_definitions_v5_7_39`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "snapshot_ping_pong_lib_corruption"
description = "lib/*.cyr edits silently revert via install-snapshot copy-back during cyrius deps"
category = "cyrius"
---
Surfaced 2026-05-03 mid-v5.8.23 bite #2 when `lib/tagged.cyr`
edits reverted between Edit calls during the sum-type migration.

== ROOT CAUSE ==

Two-step ping-pong loop:

  1. `version-bump.sh` runs `install.sh --refresh-only` which
     copies `lib/*.cyr` from the repo INTO
     `~/.cyrius/versions/<v>/lib/` and `~/.cyrius/lib`.
  2. Subsequent `cyrius deps` resolution (e.g., during
     `check.sh`) copies the snapshot version BACK into the
     repo.

If you edit a `lib/*.cyr` file AFTER a `version-bump.sh` ran
(snapshot is now stale), the next `check.sh` invocation will
overwrite your edit with the prior snapshot.

== SYMPTOM ==

You make an Edit. You verify the change. You run `check.sh`.
Tests pass. But the next time you read the file, your edit is
GONE. cc5 is also gone — the snapshot's version was pulled back
in along with the lib file, AND the snapshot's lib is what's
actually in `~/.cyrius/lib`.

== MITIGATION ==

Documented in CLAUDE.md "Snapshot-ping-pong protection
(cyrius-side `lib/*.cyr` edits)" subsection (added v5.8.26).
3-step recipe:

  1. Edit `lib/<file>.cyr`.
  2. Manually refresh the install snapshot:
     ```sh
     cp lib/<file>.cyr ~/.cyrius/versions/$(cat VERSION)/lib/<file>.cyr
     cp lib/<file>.cyr ~/.cyrius/lib/<file>.cyr
     ```
     OR run `sh scripts/version-bump.sh "$(cat VERSION)"` (same-
     version regenerate path).
  3. Run `sh scripts/check.sh` — file should now stick.

== RELATED ECOSYSTEM RULE ==

CLAUDE.md "Downstream repo setup (ecosystem rule)" forbids
downstream repos (mabda, sigil, sakshi, yukti, etc.) from
symlinking their `lib/` to `~/.cyrius/lib` because writes
through the symlink propagate up the chain into this repo.

Sakshi was found violating this at v5.8.23 (its `lib/` was a
directory-level symlink to `~/.cyrius/lib`); fixed via
`rm sakshi/lib && (cd sakshi && cyrius deps)`.

Audit script (also added to CLAUDE.md v5.8.26):
    find ~/Repos -maxdepth 2 -type l -name lib

Returns nothing now; sakshi was the only directory-level
violation. Other repos have only single-file `lib/<dep>.cyr`
symlinks (legitimate `cyrius deps` artifacts).

[[entries]]
name = "foldin_symlink_vs_regular_file"
description = "When folding a sibling distfile into cyrius's lib/ via the sandhi pattern, the vendored file MUST be a regular file (mode 100644), not the absolute-path symlink that `cyrius deps` creates by default. Symlinks point into the user's local cache (/home/<user>/.cyrius/...) and dangle on any other machine — including CI."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["foldin", "deps", "ci", "sandhi-pattern", "v5.8.65"]
content = """
**The trap**: `cyrius deps` resolves a `[deps.<name>]` entry by
populating `~/.cyrius/deps/<name>/<tag>/` and then creating
`lib/<name>.cyr` as a SYMLINK to that cache path:
```
lib/sakshi.cyr -> /home/<user>/.cyrius/deps/sakshi/2.2.3/dist/sakshi.cyr
```
The symlink target is an ABSOLUTE PATH in the resolving user's
home. On the user's local machine this works because the cache
is populated. On any OTHER machine — including GitHub Actions
CI runners (whose home is `/home/runner/...`) — the symlink
dangles.

When folding a dep into stdlib (sandhi pattern), naive `git
add lib/<name>.cyr` commits the symlink. Git records mode 120000
(symlink). On checkout elsewhere, the symlink resolves against
a non-existent path → file effectively missing.

**Surfaces as**: tcyrs that `include "lib/<name>.cyr"` fail to
compile with "file not found" → cc5 exits non-zero → under
`bash -e` (GHA's default shell mode), the test loop terminates
silently mid-loop. No `FAIL:` print, no summary, just exit 1.
Easy to misdiagnose as "test crashed the runner."

**The fix at v5.8.65** (the slot that surfaced this):
1. Convert the symlink to a regular file:
   ```
   cp --remove-destination "$(readlink lib/<name>.cyr)" lib/<name>.cyr
   ```
   `--remove-destination` is essential — `cp` without it follows
   the symlink and writes through to the cache, not the repo.
2. Commit the type change. `git diff` shows mode 120000 → 100644.
3. The cyrius distlib walker (`scripts/lib/audit-walk.sh`) skips
   files matching `^# Generated by: cyrius distlib$` in the first
   5 lines — those byte-snapshot bundles must not be reformatted.
   See also `distlib_marker_styles_v5865`.

**Recognize again**: any time you fold a `[deps.X]` into `lib/`
under the sandhi pattern, audit `git ls-tree HEAD lib/<X>.cyr`
for mode 120000 BEFORE pushing. The v5.7.0 sandhi precedent
(`lib/sandhi.cyr`) is the canonical example — mode 100644,
never a symlink.

**Why it wasn't caught locally**: the user's local machine
HAD the symlink target populated. `check.sh` self-host green,
all 127 tcyrs pass via `cyrius test`. CI is the first place
the absolute path doesn't resolve.

The fix is one shell loop, but the diagnosis took multiple
re-pushes (audit-walk marker fix, then ci.yml inline marker
fan-out, then sakshi-specific bundle.sh marker style). Saved
here so the next foldin slot starts with the de-symlink step
in the playbook.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "distlib_marker_styles_v5865"
description = "Two distlib-bundle marker styles exist in cyrius's vendored lib/: `# Generated by: cyrius distlib` (cyrius distlib output — patra/sigil/vani/yukti/sankoch/agnosys/mabda/sandhi) and `# Bundled distribution of <name>` (sakshi only — its scripts/bundle.sh predates cyrius distlib). audit-walk + ci.yml's stdlib walkers must skip BOTH."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["foldin", "audit-walk", "fmt", "lint", "sakshi", "v5.8.65"]
content = """
**The trap**: `scripts/lib/audit-walk.sh`'s
`_aw_is_distlib_bundle()` and the inline equivalents in
`.github/workflows/ci.yml`'s `Format check (stdlib)` /
`Lint (stdlib)` / `Doc coverage (stdlib)` steps used to match
exactly one marker:
```sh
head -n 5 "$f" 2>/dev/null | grep -q "^# Generated by: cyrius distlib$"
```
When sakshi was folded at v5.8.65, its dist file's header
read:
```
# sakshi.cyr — tracing, error handling, and structured logging
# Bundled distribution of sakshi v2.2.3
```
sakshi builds its dist via its own `scripts/bundle.sh`
predating cyrius's `cyrius distlib` subcommand. Different
header style. The skip-check didn't match → audit-walk ran
`cyrfmt --check` against the vendored bundle, found drift in
some indented `#` comment lines (sakshi-side bundle.sh produces
output whose indent style differs from current cyrfmt's
canonical), and the Format gate failed.

**Wrong fix would be**: apply `cyrfmt --write lib/sakshi.cyr`.
That would make lib/sakshi.cyr DIVERGE from sakshi's
dist/sakshi.cyr — breaking the byte-identity guarantee that's
the whole point of the foldin.

**Right fix**: extend the marker to recognize both styles:
```sh
head -n 5 "$f" 2>/dev/null | \
    grep -qE "^# Generated by: cyrius distlib$|^# Bundled distribution of "
```
Updated in 4 places at v5.8.65: `scripts/lib/audit-walk.sh`'s
`_aw_is_distlib_bundle` + 3 inline call sites in ci.yml
(Format/Lint/Doc-coverage stdlib steps). Mirror comment in
ci.yml notes the audit-walk equivalence so future readers know
they're paired.

**Recognize again**: any new sibling-fold whose dist generator
isn't cyrius distlib needs the marker check audited. The first
few lines of the fold-target's dist file should announce the
generator clearly. If neither `Generated by: cyrius distlib`
nor `Bundled distribution of` appears in the first 5 lines,
add the third marker style at all 4 call sites.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "heap_layout_relocation_option_a_vs_b"
description = "When growing a heap region 8x in-place collides with neighboring scratch state, the choice is Option A (in-place grow + shift downstream — monotonic, ~200+ edits) or Option B (relocate to fresh high block — non-monotonic, ~50 edits). v5.8.46 (tok arrays) + v5.8.59 (str_data) both took Option B; v5.8.61 reverted .59 back to monotonic once the gap was free."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["heap", "layout", "two-step-bootstrap", "v5.8.46", "v5.8.59", "v5.8.61"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius's heap regions have hardcoded offset
constants scattered across many files. Growing any region 8x
to absorb new data collides with whatever sits immediately
above. Two paradigms emerge:

**Option A — in-place grow + shift downstream**:
- Region stays at its original offset; size grows.
- Every region above shifts up by the size delta.
- Layout stays MONOTONIC (small-offset → big-offset reads
  cleanly).
- Cost: every offset literal in the affected band updates.
  v5.8.59 estimated this at ~200+ edits across ~20 files for
  the str_data 256 KB → 2 MB grow. Byte-identity risk grows
  linearly with edit count.

**Option B — relocate to fresh high block**:
- Region moves to a new offset above the highest-used heap.
- Size grows in the new location; old slot becomes empty.
- Layout is NON-MONOTONIC (small-offset reads jump past the
  vacant slot to the high block).
- Cost: only the offset literal changes (~50 edits).
- Precedent: v5.8.46 tok-array relocation moved
  tok_types/values/lines from `0x94A000`/`0xD4A000`/`0xF4A000`
  (tangled with output_buf) to a clean post-TS-region high
  block at `0x368C000`/`0x3E8C000`/`0x468C000`.

**The pattern that emerged**: take Option B during the
expansion slot to get the new capacity shipped fast and
audited cheaply. Pin a follow-up "monotonic reorg" slot for
when the layout-non-monotonicity becomes a maintenance
liability. v5.8.59 took Option B to ship NFKC/NFKD via the
str_data bump (placed at `0x4E8C000`); v5.8.61 reverted to
monotonic once the var_enum_id..preprocess_out gap was sized
right (str_data now at `0x21A000`). Two-step bootstrap
required at both: cc5 (old layout) compiles cc5b (new layout);
cc5b compiles cc5b'; cc5b == cc5b' byte-identical at the new
size.

**When to use which**:
- New region or major cap raise → Option B initially.
- Cycle wind-down or pre-major-bump → fold back to Option A
  (monotonic) when the receiving gap is the right size.
- DO NOT skip the two-step bootstrap audit for either path —
  heap layout changes are byte-identity-critical.

**Trade-off note**: Option B's non-monotonicity makes future
heap-map readers do mental math (str_data jumped to where?).
The follow-up monotonic reorg pays this back, but only if the
slot pin holds (don't let the "we'll reorg next minor" become
"we'll reorg next major" — pre-v6.0 hardening pin exists for
exactly this drift, see `_aw_is_distlib_bundle` mention in
the heap-map block of src/main.cyr).
"""

[[entries]]
name = "preprocess_out_vs_str_data_caps"
description = "Two distinct heap caps gate compilation. str_data caps the bytes the COMPILER writes for tracked string literals (raised to 2 MB at v5.8.59). preprocess_out caps the bytes of EXPANDED SOURCE the preprocessor produces from include resolution (still 2 MB since v5.6.40). Hitting one isn't the same as hitting the other, and the workarounds are different."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["heap", "preprocessor", "str_data", "v5.8.60"]
content = """
**The trap**: at v5.8.60 (NFKC/NFKD), the original design
used 116-char fixed-width compat-decomp records. 3833 records
× 116 chars = ~445 KB hex-encoded source — well under the
v5.8.59-bumped str_data 2 MB cap. Compiled fine in isolation.

But every consumer tcyr that includes lib/unicode/normalize.cyr
(transitively pulling in _normalize_data.cyr's ~445 KB blob)
also includes the rest of stdlib via auto-prepend. The
*expanded source* — the post-preprocessor concatenation of
all includes — overflowed `preprocess_out` (the 2 MB buffer at
S+0x44A000):
```
error: expanded source exceeds 2MB (2114828 bytes)
```
str_data has plenty of room. preprocess_out is the wall.

**These are two DIFFERENT walls**:
- `str_data` (`0x21A000`, 2 MB at v5.8.61): bytes the compiler
  writes for tracked string literals during codegen. Cap
  applies per-translation-unit.
- `preprocess_out` (`0x44A000`, 2 MB since v5.6.40): bytes of
  the source after include resolution. Cap applies BEFORE the
  lexer even runs.

A consumer that auto-prepends 14 stdlib modules + 6 sibling
distlib modules can sit at 1.6 MB expanded source even before
tcyr-specific code. Adding a 445 KB data table easily blows
the cap.

**The fix at v5.8.60**: switch the data-table encoding from
fixed-width 116-char records (445 KB total) to a 2-table
split — sorted IDX (12 chars/record × 3833 = 46 KB) +
variable-width DATA blob (count + cps, ~41 KB). Total ~87 KB,
80% reduction. Same lookup semantics (binary search IDX → data
offset → read count + cps), but consumer-side preprocess_out
stays well under cap.

**Recognize again**: any new fold-target that adds large
data blobs to lib/ should be sized against BOTH caps:
- Single-file size vs 64 KB string-literal cap (token
  encoding's u16 length field).
- Aggregate across ALL auto-prepended stdlib + the consumer's
  own source vs preprocess_out 2 MB cap.

The 2 MB preprocess_out cap is the easier one to forget
because it's not in the compiler's diagnostic surface during
single-file edits — only manifests when consumers compile.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "test_runner_pipe_capture_deadlocks_on_setuid_orphan"
description = "When a cyrius test fixture forks a setuid helper (unix_chkpwd, su, sudo, etc.), the helper inherits the test binary's stdout fd. If that fd is a pipe, the helper — reparented to init as an orphan — keeps the pipe write-end open after the test binary exits. read-to-EOF in the dispatcher blocks forever. v5.9.2 surfaced; fixed by routing capture through a temp file + waitpid-on-direct-child-only."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["test-harness", "fork", "pipe", "setuid", "orphan", "v5.9.2", "shadow_pam"]
content = """
**The trap**: a test-runner helper that captures a fixture's
stdout via the canonical fork+pipe+read-to-EOF pattern (e.g.
`lib/process.cyr`'s `exec_capture`) deadlocks when the fixture
forks a setuid grandchild that outlives the direct child.

**The shape**:

  parent (dispatcher)              -- holds rfd
   └── child (test fixture)        -- inherits wfd as fd 1
        └── grandchild (helper)    -- inherits wfd as fd 1

When child waitpid's grandchild and exits, the dispatcher reaps
the child cleanly. But if the helper survives child's exit (PAM
helpers like `unix_chkpwd` do this routinely — they're reparented
to init), the pipe still has a writer (the helper's fd 1 → wfd),
so dispatcher's `sys_read(rfd, ...)` never returns 0 (EOF).

**Specific v5.9.2 incident**: `programs/check.cyr`'s
`_tcyr_relay_gate` used `exec_capture` against `shadow_pam.tcyr`.
The .tcyr exercises `lib/pam.cyr`, which forks `unix_chkpwd`
(setuid root). PAM's child does `sys_dup2(rfd, 0)` — wires
password pipe to fd 0 — but does NOT touch fd 1 or fd 2.
unix_chkpwd inherits the dispatcher's pipe write-end and
sometimes lingers as an orphan (parent=init), keeping the pipe
open. Dispatcher's read-to-EOF blocked indefinitely.

**Why bash didn't have this problem**: the `.sh` regression-shell
equivalents pipe through `grep -q "0 failed"`. `grep -q` exits on
first match, closing its read end. The dispatcher's stdin-side of
the pipeline (the test fixture) gets SIGPIPE on next write, but
the helpers don't write to stdout so they don't trip SIGPIPE either
— they just outlive grep. The shell doesn't wait on grandchildren;
`out=$(...)` returns once grep returns.

**Fix shape (v5.9.2)**: route the fixture's stdout to a temp file
instead of a pipe. After `waitpid()` on the direct child, read
the file. Orphan grandchildren may still hold the file fd open;
we don't care — we already have the bytes the test binary wrote.

  fn _exec_capture_clean(bin_path, buf, buflen) {
      var out_path = _tmp_path("audit_cap_");
      var out_fd = sys_open(out_path, O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC, 0644);
      ...
      var pid = sys_fork();
      if (pid == 0) {
          sys_dup2(out_fd, 1);
          # /dev/null on stdin AND stderr — block any helper that
          # reads stdin or writes stderr from leaking back to the
          # dispatcher's terminal.
          ...
          sys_execve(bin_path, argv, envp);
      }
      sys_close(out_fd);
      sys_waitpid(pid, ...);   # only waits on direct child
      var n = file_read_all(out_path, buf, buflen);
      sys_unlink(out_path);
      return n;
  }

**Recognize again**:

  - Test runner that captures stdout via `exec_capture` (or any
    pipe-based fork+read pattern) and a fixture that uses
    `lib/pam.cyr` / `lib/shadow.cyr` / anything that forks a
    setuid helper.
  - Symptom: dispatcher hangs at the gate, no output, no SIGCHLD
    visible. `ps -ef` shows an orphan helper (parent=1) still
    alive.
  - Other fork-and-leave patterns will hit this too: spawn-and-
    detach daemons, double-fork helpers, anything where a
    grandchild outlives its parent and inherits fd 1.

**Prereq cousin**: v5.9.2 also fixed `_tcyr_parse_failed` — its
inner digit-walkback loop infinite-looped when the byte before
" failed" was a digit (i.e., every PASS path matching `0 failed`).
Combined with the pipe deadlock above, the v5.9.1 commit shipping
`_tcyr_relay_gate` had two prereq bugs that masked each other:
even if one was fixed, the other would have surfaced. The
underlying lesson is *commit-with-end-to-end-verification*: a
helper that compiles is not a helper that works.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "parse_var_struct_init_lookahead_v5933"
description = "PARSE_VAR / EMIT_GVAR_INITS / PARSE_GVAR_REG must require next-next token to be `{` before committing to PARSE_STRUCT_INIT. Without the lookahead, any `var X = ident <op> ...` where `ident` matches a struct name errored 'expected {, got <op>'. Surfaces only when the bug-triggering fn body is parsed (DCE-bitmap masks the bug on x86; aarch64 reveals it because syscalls is bigger)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["parser", "struct-init", "dce", "tok_names-dedup", "v5.9.33", "agnosys-1.1.12"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius does no namespacing — a struct named
`status` and a fn parameter named `status` share the same
`tok_names` offset because `LEXID` dedups identifier storage.
After pass 1 registers `status` in `struct_names[]`, pass 2's
PARSE_VAR sees `var sig = status & 0x7F;` inside a fn body
that declared `(status)` as its parameter. The local-var
parser does:

```
if (PEEKT(S) == 2) {
    var sn = PEEKV(S);
    var sid = FINDSTRUCT(S, sn);
    if (sid > 0) {
        PARSE_STRUCT_INIT(S, noff, sid);  # commits unconditionally
        return 0;
    }
}
```

`FINDSTRUCT` hits because the offset matches the struct name.
PARSE_STRUCT_INIT consumes the ident and demands `{`; the
actual next token is `&` (token 27, missing from `TOKNAME`),
producing `error:N: expected '{', got unknown`.

**Why aarch64 surfaced and x86 didn't**: cyrius runs a DCE
pre-scan in `src/main.cyr` that walks the token stream, marks
ident references in an 8 KB bitmap covering offsets `[0,
65536)`, and emits a 3-byte stub (`xor eax,eax; ret`) for any
fn whose name offset is *inside* the bitmap window AND
unreferenced. Offsets `≥ 65536` are conservative-kept (the
DCE check is gated on `dce_fnoff < 65536`).

`lib/syscalls_aarch64_linux.cyr` (677 LOC) is bigger than
`lib/syscalls_x86_64_linux.cyr` (630 LOC). On x86, `WIFSIGNALED`
(an unreferenced library fn) lands inside the window and is
DCE-stubbed before parse — masking the parser bug entirely.
On aarch64, the same fn's offset lands ≥ 65536, DCE skips,
the body is fully parsed, and the parser trips.

**Fix at v5.9.33** (`src/frontend/parse_decl.cyr`): three
sites — `PARSE_VAR` (~line 998), `EMIT_GVAR_INITS` (~line
615), `PARSE_GVAR_REG` (~line 540) — each require
`TOKTYP(S, GTI(S) + 1) == 13` (next-next token is `{`)
before committing to PARSE_STRUCT_INIT. Bare ident
references fall through to scalar expression parsing where
they belong. Pass 1's `PARSE_GVAR_REG` is the most subtle of
the three: pre-fix it set `is_struct = 1` and allocated
`STRUCTSZ` bytes for the var slot, corrupting downstream
codegen for any global `var x = MASK & 0xF;` where MASK was
also a struct name; the fix gates the `is_struct = 1`
assignment on the same lookahead.

**Recognize again**: any `expected '{', got <symbol>` error
where the offending source is `var X = NAME ...;` and `NAME`
was elsewhere declared as a `struct`. Specifically when the
arch-pair behavior splits — works on x86, breaks on
aarch64 (or vice versa) — the difference is almost always
DCE-window-position, not a real arch difference. To
narrow: `cat src.cyr | build/cc5_aarch64 2>&1 | grep -E
'(unreachable|dead:)'` shows what got DCE'd; if a fn name
appears on x86's dead list but not aarch64's, suspect a
bug masked by DCE on the smaller arch.

**Lesson for future parser additions**: any
`if (FINDSTRUCT(...) > 0) { commit_to_struct_path(); }`
pattern needs a `{` lookahead. The pattern can also appear in
`PARSE_FN_DEF`'s return-type lookahead, `PARSE_FIELD_LOAD`,
and anywhere else struct-name resolution gates a parser path
choice. This is the second time tok_names-dedup has caused
parser confusion (the first was v5.7.46
`fn_keyword_in_param_position`); when in doubt, peek
further before committing.

Full backstory: agnosys 1.1.12 V1.1.12 evaluation, filed
2026-05-07; cyrius `tests/tcyr/struct_name_param_collision.tcyr`
covers 13 assertions across this shape.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "pp_in_string_comment_blindness_v5934"
description = "PP_IFDEF_PASS / PP_PASS `in_string` state machine added at v5.8.40 was comment-blind — `\"` characters inside line comments toggled `in_string=1` and stayed stuck across newlines, masking later `include` directives. Comment-aware tracking + reset-on-newline fix landed v5.9.34."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["preprocessor", "string-state-machine", "include-resolution", "v5.9.34", "vyakarana-1.0.2"]
content = """
**The trap**: v5.8.40 added `in_string` tracking to PP_PASS
and PP_IFDEF_PASS to keep `var s = "include \\"foo\\"";` from
being mistaken for an include directive. The directive-
detection block was gated on `bol == 1 && in_string == 0`.
The state machine handled `"` (toggle) and `\\X` (escape next
byte inside string) correctly for actual string literals.

It did NOT handle:
1. **Comments** — `# foo "bar"` would toggle `in_string` on
   each `"` regardless of comment context.
2. **`#` mid-line** — trailing comments like
   `var x = 0;  # explanation with "quote"` had the same
   issue.
3. **Stray `"` in comments** — vyakarana 1.0.2's
   `src/grammar.cyr` documenting JSON escape syntax with
   `` # references inside strings: `\\\\`, `\\"`, ``. The
   `` `\\"` `` (backtick + backslash + quote + backtick)
   pattern: outside a string, `\\` was a no-op; the next `"`
   toggled `in_string=1`; there was no closing `"` on that
   or any subsequent line until much later. `in_string`
   stayed 1 through every later `include` directive in
   included files.

The symptom downstream: `cyrius build src/main.cyr build/...`
fails with `error:<some-included-file>:N: expected '=', got
string` AT the include directive itself. `include` was
tokenized as an identifier (its directive status lost when
PP_IFDEF_PASS skipped it via the `in_string` gate), so the
parser saw `include "src/X.cyr"` as `IDENT STRING` and
expected an `=` between them.

**Why minimal repros didn't trigger** (vyakarana filing's
"ruled-out hypotheses" section): the filing's bisect chased
structural include-graph shapes (sibling-transitive,
duplicate, nested chain). The actual trigger was the
`\\"` comment, which the structural minimal-repros didn't
include. Any include graph would break IF the included
content has a `\\"`-bearing comment upstream of an include
directive — structural shape was incidental.

**Fix at v5.9.34** (`src/frontend/lex_pp.cyr`): both PP_PASS
(~line 1430) and PP_IFDEF_PASS (~line 1770) state machines
made comment-aware:

1. New `in_comment` state alongside `in_string` /
   `escape_next`.
2. `#` outside a string (and outside a comment already) sets
   `in_comment = 1`.
3. Inside a comment, `"` does NOT toggle `in_string` —
   state machine routes through a simpler path that just
   tracks the newline.
4. Newline resets `in_string = 0`, `escape_next = 0`,
   `in_comment = 0` as a safety net. cyrius source uses
   single-line strings (`\\n` escape, never literal multi-
   line), so per-line state reset is safe and bounds any
   future state corruption to one line.

**Recognize again**: any `expected '=', got string` error
where the offending source is `include "..."`-shaped at the
top of an included file. If the build was working before
v5.8.40 and broken at v5.8.40+, the trigger is almost
certainly a `\\"` (or other unmatched `"`) inside a comment
upstream of the failing include. To diagnose:

```sh
# Search the project's already-included files for
# unmatched-or-stray quotes in comments
grep -rn '#.*\\\\"' src/ lib/
```

Lines that match are candidates for the trigger.

**Lesson**: PP state machines that mirror lexer string
tracking need to mirror ALL the lexer's lexical rules —
strings AND comments AND char literals. The per-line reset
on newline is a cheap safety net that bounds bugs to one
line rather than the whole compilation unit. Adding it
preemptively in similar state machines is good defensive
practice.

Full backstory: vyakarana 1.0.2 pin-bump 5.6.0 → 5.9.32 at
2026-05-07; filed at
`vyakarana/docs/development/issues/2026-05-07-cyrius-include-graph-regression.md`;
cyrius `tests/tcyr/include_quote_comment.tcyr` (3 assertions)
+ `tests/fixtures/include_quote_comment/{leaf,sibling_a,
sibling_b}.cyr` cover the regression.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "macho_arm64_pie_aslr_static_fn_addr"
description = "Mach-O ARM64 enforces MH_PIE; dyld slides the image at load time. Static-encoded absolute fn addresses (3-instruction MOVZ/MOVK chain in `&fn_name` ftype==3 fixup) survive ELF but NOT Mach-O — `blr xN` jumps to (file_VA, no slide), landing in `__data` / `__got` instead of `__text`. v5.9.39 fix: dispatch ftype==3 to ADRP+ADD relative addressing on `_TARGET_MACHO == 2`, mirroring how ftype==1 (string addrs) and ftype==0 (var addrs) already worked. The shape: any fixup type encoding an absolute address must be PIE-safe on Mach-O."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["macho", "aarch64", "fixup", "aslr", "pie", "v5.9.39", "fn-pointer"]
content = """
v5.9.38/v5.9.39 paired bug. Symptom: agnosys 1.1.12 verbatim
repro SIGSEGV'd at runtime on real macOS arm64 (ecb host)
inside the heavy-allocator-vtable dispatch chain that
`#derive(Serialize)` triggers.

== TWO COMPOUNDING BUGS ==

**Bug A** (v5.9.38, simple once seen): `lib/fnptr.cyr` had
`#ifdef CYRIUS_TARGET_LINUX` and `#ifdef CYRIUS_TARGET_WIN`
branches in `fncall0..8`, but no `#ifdef CYRIUS_TARGET_MACOS`.
On Mach-O builds, neither asm{} block fired → `result`
stayed at the `var result = 0;` init → fncallN always
returned 0 → `alloc_via` returned NULL → str_builder_new
returned NULL → SIGSEGV at `load64(NULL+8)`. Fix: add
macOS branches with x86_64 + aarch64 asm copies of the
Linux content (SysV calling convention identical).

**Bug B** (v5.9.39, the deeper one): even with Bug A
fixed, the binary got further but still SIGSEGV'd — now
at addr 5 (`ldrb w0, [x0]` with x0=5). Tracking down
showed PC inside what looked like a memcpy/strlen
alignment loop. The actual cause: `&fn_name` aarch64
emit emitted a static 3-instruction MOVZ/MOVK chain
encoding the unslid file VA. Apple Silicon enforces
MH_PIE; dyld slides the image at load time; `blr xN`
jumped to (file_VA, no slide) — landing in `__data` /
`__got` instead of `__text`. Runtime alloc_fn value was
`0x100017C00`, past the `__text` end (`0x10000C504`).

== THE FIX ==

Mirror what ftype==1 (string addrs) and ftype==0 (var
addrs) already did on Mach-O: dispatch to
`FIXUP_ADRP_ADD` which encodes the page-diff in the
ADRP's immhi/immlo and the low-12 bits in the ADD's
imm12. Both halves are PC-relative; the slide cancels
out; `blr xN` lands in `__text` correctly.

Three coordinated edits (v5.9.39):
- `src/backend/aarch64/fixup.cyr` ftype==3: dispatch to
  `FIXUP_ADRP_ADD(S, coff, ftarget)` on
  `_TARGET_MACHO == 2`, `FIXUP_MOV` otherwise.
- `src/frontend/parse_expr.cyr` `&fn_name` aarch64 emit:
  emit 2-instruction ADRP+ADD pair (8 B) on Mach-O
  instead of 3-instruction MOVZ chain (12 B).
- `src/frontend/parse_expr.cyr` closure-literal aarch64
  emit: same change.

Plus `src/backend/x86/emit.cyr`: stub `EADRP` and
`EADD_IMM12` so the x86 build's dead-code branch through
`_AARCH64_BACKEND == 1` resolves the symbols cleanly.

== FIELD NOTE FOR THE NEXT AGENT ==

When Mach-O ARM crashes at runtime in code that "should
work because it works on Linux aarch64" — check ASLR/PIE
first. Mach-O is always slid; static absolute fn addresses
do not survive.

The audit shape: every fixup type that encodes an
ABSOLUTE address must be PIE-safe on Mach-O. ftype==1,
ftype==0, ftype==5 (Mach-O __got slot) all use ADRP+ADD
or ADRP+LDR. ftype==3 was the missing one — fixed at
v5.9.39. If a new fixup type lands, it needs the same
audit.

The regression substrate is `_macho_derive_serialize_gate`
in `programs/check.cyr` (v5.9.39 ship). Compiles + scp's +
codesigns + runs a fixture that exercises the exact
Bug-A-and-Bug-B chain via `point_to_json(&p, sb)`. If
either bug regresses the gate flips red.

CROSS-REPO RECEIPT:
- agnosys 1.1.12 verbatim repro hash
  `6425355b6147d5a674078794310ae2c1` (preserved unchanged
  through the v5.9.33-39 partial-fix chain — see
  `feedback_no_rewriting_consumer_repros` memory pin).
- Cross-host parity verified at v5.9.39 ship: Mach-O ARM
  matches Linux aarch64 byte-for-byte through
  `point_to_json(&p, sb)`. Both fail at the same
  `println(strlen(out))` line — that's a TYPE-SYSTEM gap
  pinned for v5.10.x, not a Mach-O codegen bug.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "lex_brace_count_when_inserting_dispatch_branch"
description = "Inserting a new top-level dispatch branch into `src/frontend/lex.cyr`'s deeply-nested `else { if (...) { ... } }` cascade requires matching the closing brace count exactly. v5.9.37 char-literal addition initially had a brace imbalance; the resulting parse error pointed at `src/backend/x86/emit.cyr:340` because that's the FIRST file the mis-parsed parser hits, not the actual cause-site (lex.cyr's missing close)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["lexer", "syntax", "v5.9.37", "brace-count", "diagnostic-mislead"]
content = """
v5.9.37 added char-literal lexing. The implementation
lives in `src/frontend/lex.cyr` around line 988 (between
the `c == 37` percent-symbol branch and the `c == 34`
string-literal branch), inserted as ~50 lines of new code.

== THE BRACE-COUNT GOTCHA ==

When inserting the char-literal branch into lex.cyr's
deeply-nested if/else dispatch chain, the closing brace
count needs to match the opened branches exactly. The
initial v5.9.37 attempt had a brace imbalance — adding
`else { if (c == 39) { ... }` without the matching
closing `}` produced this self-host build error:

    error:src/backend/x86/emit.cyr:340:
        undefined variable '_cur_fn_regalloc'

The error points at emit.cyr — but the cause is in
lex.cyr. The mis-parsed parser misinterpreted emit.cyr's
top-level structure (because the missing brace in lex.cyr
shifted every subsequent file's parse context), and the
FIRST symbol that broke was `_cur_fn_regalloc` in emit.cyr.

Fix: add one extra `}` to the closing brace chain at
lex.cyr line 1241 (the end of the dispatch ladder).

== FIELD NOTE FOR THE NEXT AGENT ==

When inserting a new top-level dispatch branch into
lex.cyr or any deeply-nested else-if chain in cyrius
source, count braces before building. The cascade in
lex.cyr is ~600 lines deep; adding a branch in the middle
needs the matching close at the bottom.

If self-host fails with an "undefined variable" error in
a file you didn't touch this slot, brace imbalance in a
file you DID touch is the first thing to check. cyrius's
parser is single-pass; brace-count drift cascades silently
into subsequent files.

The diagnostic message is misleading by accident — the
parser reports the FIRST symbol it can't resolve, not
the original brace error. Don't trust the file name in
the error message; check the file you most recently
edited for unbalanced braces.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "char_literal_token_emits_number_type"
description = "Char literals `'X'` (v5.9.37) emit NUMBER token (type 1) carrying the byte value. Indistinguishable at parser layer from `var x = 65;`. Standard escapes supported (\\n / \\t / \\r / \\\\ / \\' / \\0). Single-byte ASCII only — no multi-byte / unicode in char literals."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["lexer", "syntax", "v5.9.37", "char-literal"]
content = """
v5.9.37 added char-literal lexing for the agnosys 1.1.12
verbatim repro (which used `str_builder_putc(sb, '[')`).

== WHAT IT EMITS ==

A NUMBER token (token type 1) carrying the byte value:
    'A'   → 65
    'a'   → 97
    ' '   → 32
    '['   → 91
    '\\n'  → 10
    '\\t'  → 9
    '\\\\'  → 92
    '\\''  → 39
    '\\0'  → 0

Indistinguishable at the parser layer from `var x = 65;`
or `if (c == 65) { ... }` — the parser sees a NUMBER
token, not a "char-literal" token. That's intentional:
char literals are sugar for byte values, not a separate
type.

== CONSEQUENCE ==

Type system (when it lands at v5.10.x) won't have a
distinct "char" type. `'A'` and `65` are interchangeable.
That matches C's char-as-int semantics rather than Rust's
char-as-Unicode-codepoint. Cyrius works at the byte
level by design (no SIMD, no unicode-aware ops in the
compiler itself); char literals follow the same model.

If a consumer later wants `char` as a distinct narrow-
int type (i8 typed-narrow), it can already be expressed
via the v5.9.36 narrow-int #derive(Serialize) machinery:
    struct ascii_byte { c: i8; }
That gets you i8 typing without needing a new char type.

== PAIRED ADDITION ==

`lib/str.cyr` gained `str_builder_putc(sb, ch)` in the
same slot — appends single byte to a str_builder. Mirrors
the existing `str_builder_add` (Str),
`str_builder_add_cstr` (cstring), `str_builder_add_int`
helpers; pairs with char literals for byte-at-a-time
append.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "f64v_simd_frame_disp_under_regalloc"
description = "Pre-v5.10.16 EMIT_F64V_LOOP/UNARY/FMADD in src/backend/x86/float.cyr computed slot disps as -(N+1)*8 while EFLSTORE adjusted by additional _cur_fn_regalloc * 8 + _cur_fn_ret_stash. Any caller fn that auto-enabled the regalloc cache segfaulted reading 40+ bytes off the stash. Latent ~3.5 yr — only consumer (programs/simd_expand_test.cyr) was never wired into check.sh."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["codegen", "frame", "regalloc", "simd", "x86", "v5.10.16"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius's frame addressing has TWO flavors.

Local-load helpers (`EFLSTORE`, `EFLLOAD`, `EFLADDR`) apply
THREE adjustments to the raw slot-N → `-(N+1)*8` disp:
- `_cur_fn_regalloc * 8` — callee-save register save slots
  (when auto-regalloc fires, x86 inserts 5 stash slots
  before the locals; +40 bytes of prologue).
- `_cur_fn_ret_stash` — hidden retbuf-arg stash for
  struct-returning fns (+8 bytes).
- The cumulative offset shifts every local slot DOWN by
  `regalloc * 8 + ret_stash`.

Direct emits that compute disps inline (the SIMD f64v_*
loops, possibly other places) MUST apply the same
adjustment, or the load disp diverges from the store
disp by 40+ bytes — first iteration reads off the stash
into rdx (or wherever), segfault on next memory access.

== HOW WE FOUND IT ==

v5.10.16 slot scope was "close cross-arch SIMD gap":
implement aarch64 NEON for f64v_*, since aarch64 had
`return 0;` stubs. Premise check (per
`feedback_premise_check_at_slot_entry`) — write a tcyr
regression to lock the behavior. tcyr binary segfaulted
on x86 in the FIRST f64v_add call. Bisected vs older
cc5 versions back to v5.10.0 — they all segfaulted
identically. So the bug wasn't introduced by aarch64
work; it was a latent x86 bug that pre-dated the
cross-arch claim. The claim "in production since
v1.9.0" was wrong: only worked on x86 fns without
auto-regalloc enabled (rare in stdlib code, common
in user code).

== THE FIX (v5.10.16) ==

Factored a `_F64V_DISP(idx)` helper in
`src/backend/x86/float.cyr` that mirrors EFLSTORE's
adjustment formula. Also switched the load form from
disp8 (`48 8B 55 disp8`) to disp32 (`48 8B 95 disp32`)
— the disp8 mask `& 0xFF` silently truncates if the
adjusted disp drops below -128. With +40 of regalloc
adjustment, even modest vbase values can cross that
boundary; +3 bytes per load is amortized across the
loop.

== HOW TO RECOGNIZE IT AGAIN ==

Two-finger smell test for any direct frame-emit code:
1. Does it compute disp as `-(N+1)*8` directly?
2. Does it apply `_cur_fn_regalloc * 8 + _cur_fn_ret_
   stash` adjustment?

If yes/no, that emit will segfault under auto-regalloc.
Search `src/backend/x86/` for `(0 - (vbase` or
`(N + 1) * 8` and audit each one against EFLSTORE's
formula. The cross-arch peer on `src/backend/aarch64/`
should ALWAYS route through `EFLLOAD` for the same
reason (and v5.10.16's aarch64 NEON impl does — that's
why aarch64 doesn't have this bug post-fix).

== ROOT-CAUSE PATTERN ==

This is the "two flavors of frame addressing" pattern.
Cyrius has been growing direct-emit codepaths for hot
paths (SIMD primitives, struct-init, slice canonical
slot) — each one is a place where the regalloc/ret-
stash adjustment could be missed. Long-term fix is
either factor ALL frame-disp computation through
EFLSTORE/EFLLOAD (forcing the adjustment), or add an
audit gate that scans for raw `(idx + 1) * 8` patterns
in backend code.

For now: any new direct-emit slot that touches frame
slots MUST mirror the EFLSTORE adjustment formula.
Use `_F64V_DISP` (now in x86/float.cyr) as the
reference template.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "api_surface_brace_counter_string_skip"
description = "Pre-v5.10.16 programs/cyrius_api_surface.cyr walked source files counting { / } bytes raw — { inside JSON-emit string literals like \"{\\\"x\\\":\" inflated depth and the scanner concluded enclosing fns never closed. Every fn / struct decl after that point in the same module silently dropped from the surface. Same bug class as cyrlint v5.10.10 char-literal-brace-desync. Fix: skip strings + char literals + # comments before counting."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["api-surface", "lexer", "scanner", "v5.10.16", "agnosys-1.1.13"]
content = """
**The pattern**: raw byte-counters that need to handle
cyrius's literal forms.

Scanner-style tools (cyrlint, cyrfmt, cyrius_api_surface)
walk source files at the byte level rather than going
through cc5's full lexer. They count `{` and `}` bytes
to track block depth. WITHOUT skip-strings, skip-chars,
and skip-comments handling, ANY `{` or `}` byte inside
those forms is counted wrongly:

- A `{` inside a JSON literal like `"{\\\"x\\\":"`
  inflates depth — fns after this line look like
  they're inside a block, scanner skips fn-declaration
  logic.
- A `}` inside `"}"` deflates depth (often correctly
  cancelling a phantom `{` from above, so the bug only
  shows on UNBALANCED string content).
- A `}` inside a char literal deflates depth.
- A `{` inside a `# comment with { in it` inflates.

== THE AGNOSYS FILING WAS MIS-DIAGNOSED ==

Filed 2026-05-09 as
`2026-05-09-cyrius-api-surface-putc-brace-desync`.
Their hypothesis: `str_builder_putc(sb, 125)` — the
literal `125` (ASCII for `}`) was being read as a
`}` byte. That hypothesis is WRONG: the source bytes
of `125` are `1` (49), `2` (50), `5` (53) — none equal
123 or 125. The byte-level counter has no way to
misread them.

Actual cause: their fn `widget_a_to_json` opened with
a JSON `add_cstr` call containing a literal `{` byte
inside the string. That `{` was counted as a real
opening brace, depth went to 2 inside what should have
been a depth-1 fn body, and depth never returned to 0
for the rest of the file. Every subsequent fn / struct
decl was lost.

Their workaround `str_builder_add_cstr(sb, "}")` to
emit the closing brace happened to add a `}` byte that
balanced the phantom `{` — that's why the workaround
worked, not because `125` vs `"}"` differed in any
scanner-relevant way.

== HOW TO RECOGNIZE IT AGAIN ==

Any new scanner-style tool added under `programs/` that
walks `.cyr` source byte-by-byte. If it's counting any
delimiter pair (`{`/`}`, `(`/`)`, `[`/`]`) without
literal-skip handling, it's broken on at least one
input shape. Templates are in cyrlint v5.10.10 and
api-surface v5.10.16.

The proper long-term fix is to add a shared
`programs/lib/scanner_skip.cyr` helper so every
scanner-tool routes through the same skip pattern. For
now (v5.10.16) each scanner duplicates the pattern
inline.
"""


[[entries]]
name = "locname_staleness_duplicate_dispatch_paths"
description = "Locname-table staleness bug class — same pattern surfaces independently in EACH parse path that uses bare EFLSTORE for arg-stash slots. v5.10.35 fixed PARSE_SIMD_EXT (ptyp 93-130); missed the SEPARATE f64v_add/sub/mul dispatch at ptyp 89-91 in parse_expr.cyr. v5.10.39 paid the duplicate-path debt. When fixing locname/table-related bugs, audit ALL dispatchers that might share the pattern."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["cyrius", "compiler", "parse", "locname", "stash", "simd", "v5.10.35", "v5.10.39"]
content = """
THE BUG CLASS

Cyrius's locname table at `S + 0x191000` is per-fn-body but
shares allocation across fn parses (SFLC(0) resets the FLC
counter but NOT the locname entries past the new FLC).
Stale name entries from PRIOR fn parses persist at higher
indices.

When a parse path stashes an arg value at slot N via
`EFLSTORE(S, N)` WITHOUT also clearing locname[N], it leaves
a stale name visible to FINDLOCAL. If that stale name happens
to equal a var the current fn body subsequently looks up
(e.g. `return r;` after using the var name `r`), FINDLOCAL
returns the STASH slot index (containing the pointer-VALUE
that was stored as the arg) instead of the real var's slot.

CLASSIC SHAPE

```cyr
fn wrap(p): f64v2 {
    var r: f64v2;
    f64v_add(&r, p, p, 2);  # arg-stash at slot N; locname[N] stale "r"
    return r;                # FINDLOCAL("r") returns N, loads stash
}
```

The `return r;` emits a pair-register load from slot N (the
stash slot, holding &r's pointer-value), NOT from r's actual
slot. Caller gets a stack-address-shaped i64 back instead
of the f64v2 bytes.

THE FIX HELPER

```cyr
fn _SIMD_STASH(S, idx): i64 {
    EFLSTORE(S, idx);
    S64(S + 0x191000 + idx * 8, 0 - 1);  # anonymise
    return 0;
}
```

Wrap EVERY bare-EFLSTORE-for-arg-stash with this. The
locname[idx] = -1 marks the slot as anonymous; FINDLOCAL
skips it.

THE DUPLICATE-PATH TRAP

v5.10.35 applied _SIMD_STASH to the 8 intrinsics in
PARSE_SIMD_EXT (ptyp 93 / 94 / 95 / 96 / 128 / 129 / 130 +
bitset/bitclr 103/104). The fix DID NOT cover f64v_add /
_sub / _mul at ptyp 89-91, which live in a SEPARATE
dispatch block in parse_expr.cyr (around line 1397, NOT
inside PARSE_SIMD_EXT).

That separate block continued to use bare EFLSTORE. The bug
stayed latent because pre-v5.10.39 lib/simd.cyr had a stable
locname layout (only pointer-form wrappers, ~10 fns). When
v5.10.39 doubled the simd.cyr fn count (adding value-form
siblings), locname churn made the stale-collision reliable.

Bisection (v5.10.39 in-slot): reverting lib/simd.cyr made
the test pass with v5.10.39 dispatch in place → isolated to
lib/simd.cyr changes. Direct `f64v2_add_ptr(&x, &y)` ALSO
failed → isolated to body (not overload routing). Same
locname-staleness shape; different parse path.

HOW TO AUDIT FOR DUPLICATES

When fixing a locname/stash/table bug:

1. Grep for ALL call sites of the EFLSTORE family in the
   parser code (not just the file you're editing):
   `grep -rn "EFLSTORE(S, vbase\|EFLSTORE(S, [a-z]" src/frontend/`
2. For each, verify locname[idx] is set (= -1 for anonymous
   stash, or = name_offset for named) IMMEDIATELY after the
   EFLSTORE call.
3. Bare EFLSTORE without a locname companion is the bug.
4. Apply the fix at the call site OR refactor to a wrapped
   _STASH helper.

LESSON: The first occurrence of a bug class fixed in slot X
is the "this is the bug" anchor. The FIX should AUDIT for
the bug class across the entire compiler, not assume the
first occurrence is the only one. v5.10.35 was a complete-
seeming fix that left an entire dispatch path with the same
bug; v5.10.39 paid the cost.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "install_sh_cp_L_same_file_silent_fail"
description = "install.sh's --refresh-only path uses `cp -L lib/*.cyr` to copy stdlib into snapshot. When lib/<dep>.cyr is a `cyrius deps`-resolved symlink AND the snapshot dir has a parallel symlink to the SAME real file, cp -L exits with 'same file' error. `set -e` makes this fatal — install.sh exits BEFORE the symlink-update block at line 249-251. ~/.cyrius/bin / ~/.cyrius/current stay pointing at the previous version. Discovered v5.10.37."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["cyrius", "install", "deps", "symlink", "set-e", "v5.10.37", "v5.10.46"]
content = """
WHAT BREAKS

After `sh scripts/version-bump.sh 5.10.X`, expected end state:
- `cat ~/.cyrius/current` → 5.10.X
- `readlink ~/.cyrius/bin` → ~/.cyrius/versions/5.10.X/bin
- `~/.cyrius/bin/cc5 --version` → cc5 5.10.X

Observed (multi-bump streak in v5.10.x cycle):
- ~/.cyrius/current → stale (5.10.34 e.g.)
- readlink ~/.cyrius/bin → stale version's bin
- cc5 --version → stale 5.10.34

User-visible symptom: `cyrius-prompt-info tool` (which reads
through ~/.cyrius/bin/cc5) shows wrong toolchain version on
the user's starship prompt. Easy to mis-read as "starship.toml
corruption" — actual config bytes are intact, but the cyrius
prompt segments render with stale data.

ROOT CAUSE

scripts/install.sh's --refresh-only fast path includes a
lib-copy loop (around line 224):

```sh
while IFS= read -r f; do
    rel="${f#lib/}"
    dst="$CYRIUS_HOME/versions/$VERSION/lib/$rel"
    mkdir -p "$(dirname "$dst")"
    cp -L "$f" "$dst"   # ← FAILS with "same file" for symlink colliders
    _lib_count=$((_lib_count + 1))
done <<EOF_LIB
$(find -L lib -type f -name '*.cyr')
EOF_LIB
```

When `lib/mabda.cyr` is a `cyrius deps`-resolved symlink into
`~/.cyrius/deps/mabda/3.0.0-rc.2/dist/mabda.cyr`, AND the
snapshot at `~/.cyrius/versions/$VERSION/lib/mabda.cyr` is
ALSO a symlink to the same real file (set up by a prior
refresh that ran when the deps target was the same version),
`cp -L` dereferences BOTH and sees source and destination
resolve to the same inode:

```
cp: 'lib/mabda.cyr' and '/home/macro/.cyrius/versions/$VER/lib/mabda.cyr' are the same file
```

install.sh's top-level `set -e` makes this exit code fatal.
The script exits before reaching the symlink-update block:

```sh
# install.sh:249-251 (NEVER RUNS when cp -L fails)
rm -rf "$CYRIUS_HOME/bin" "$CYRIUS_HOME/lib"
ln -sf "$CYRIUS_HOME/versions/$VERSION/bin" "$CYRIUS_HOME/bin"
ln -sf "$CYRIUS_HOME/versions/$VERSION/lib" "$CYRIUS_HOME/lib"
```

So ~/.cyrius/bin / ~/.cyrius/lib / ~/.cyrius/current stay
pointing at whichever version was previously active.

HOW TO DETECT IT MANUALLY

After version-bump.sh, verify:

```sh
test "$(readlink ~/.cyrius/bin | sed 's|.*/versions/||;s|/bin||')" = "$(cat VERSION)" || echo "SYMLINK STALE"
```

If the readlink doesn't match VERSION, install.sh exited
before the symlink dance. Re-run with:

```sh
rm -rf ~/.cyrius/{bin,lib} && \
  ln -sf ~/.cyrius/versions/$(cat VERSION)/bin ~/.cyrius/bin && \
  ln -sf ~/.cyrius/versions/$(cat VERSION)/lib ~/.cyrius/lib && \
  echo "$(cat VERSION)" > ~/.cyrius/current
```

FIX (pinned v5.10.46 closeout)

Two-part fix:
1. **Primary** — change `cyrius deps` to physical-copy
   lib/<dep>.cyr instead of symlinking. Eliminates the
   inode-collision root cause at the architectural layer.
   (Option C from the v5.10.37 user discussion.)
2. **Belt-and-suspenders** — replace `cp -L` with
   `rm -f "$dst" && cp -L` (always nuke dst first) AND add
   a tail-of-refresh-only verification that `readlink
   ~/.cyrius/bin` matches the new version with hard-fail
   if not.

The verification step would have caught this bug in seconds
instead of multiple observations across slots; silent-skip
is the worst kind of failure mode.

LESSON: Install scripts running with `set -e` that perform
multi-step state transitions MUST verify their end-state at
the tail and hard-fail if not consistent. Silent partial-
success is unrecoverable from the user's perspective. The
two version-discovery paths (`cyrius --version` reading
VERSION file directly vs `cyrius-prompt-info tool` reading
through ~/.cyrius/bin/cc5) diverged for multiple version
bumps before anyone noticed.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "stack_local_scratch_buffer_overflow_at_dispatch"
description = "Stack-local scratch buffer overflow corrupts adjacent locals — symptom is `fi` / `noff` (in parse_fn.cyr's PARSE_FNCALL) holding wrong values after the overflow, producing miscompiled call sites. v5.10.39 first cut had `var _po_scratch[16]` for constructing `<base>_ptr` overload-lookup strings; overflowed for any base name ≥12 chars (e.g. `f64v2_add_ptr` direct call constructs `f64v2_add_ptr_ptr` = 18 bytes). Sized check + bumped scratch to 128 bytes."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["cyrius", "compiler", "parse", "stack-local", "overflow", "v5.10.39"]
content = """
THE PATTERN

When constructing scratch strings on the stack for compile-time
lookups (e.g. building `<base_name>_ptr` for overload dispatch),
the stack-local array MUST be sized to accommodate the LARGEST
possible base name + suffix + null terminator, NOT a typical case.

SHAPE

```cyr
fn dispatch(noff): i64 {
    var _scratch[16];   # ← too small for many fn names
    var base_len = strlen(S + 0x60000 + noff);
    # ... copy base_len bytes into scratch ...
    # ... append "_ptr\0" (5 bytes) ...
    # ↑ overflow if base_len > 11
}
```

For "f64v2_add_ptr" (13 chars) + "_ptr\0" (5 chars) = 18
bytes. Writes at offsets 16, 17 overflow a 16-byte scratch
into adjacent stack data — typically the next stack-local
or saved caller-state. In parse_fn.cyr's PARSE_FNCALL the
overflow corrupted the `fi` / `noff` variables, producing
silently-miscompiled call sites that returned wrong values.

WHY 16 BYTES SEEMED SAFE

The dispatch was originally designed for cyrius's own SIMD
wrapper names (`f64v2_add`, 9 chars). "f64v2_add" + "_ptr\0"
fits in 14 bytes → comfortable in 16-byte scratch. The
overflow path was when the dispatch ITSELF fires for a fn
WHOSE NAME ALREADY ENDS IN `_ptr` — e.g. a direct call to
`f64v2_add_ptr(&x, &y)` (which doesn't need rerouting) still
runs the dispatch and constructs `f64v2_add_ptr_ptr`.

The non-found lookup returns -1 and no reroute happens, but
the WRITE to scratch already corrupted adjacent memory.

THE FIX

Bump scratch size to be safely larger than ALL realistic
fn names + suffix. v5.10.39 went with 128 bytes (`_po_scratch
[128]`) — accommodates any fn name within the 120-char
defensive guard. Pattern:

```cyr
var _scratch[128];
if (base_len < 120) {
    # ... safe to write up to base_len + suffix_len ...
}
```

Plus the explicit `base_len < 120` guard provides defense
in depth if base names ever grow past expected.

LESSON: When sizing stack-local scratch buffers for compile-
time string construction, target a generous CAP that
accommodates the worst realistic input, not a "typical" case.
Stack corruption is silent and only manifests as miscompiled
output downstream — extremely hard to diagnose without
bisection. Pre-fix v5.10.39 had MANY hours of debugging time
spent before the overflow was identified.

DIAGNOSTIC SIGNS

If a compile-time dispatch fires for some call sites but
produces wrong results, AND reverting the dispatch resolves
it, AND the wrong result has the shape of a stack address —
suspect stack-local overflow in the dispatch code.
"""
